---
import PageLayout from "@layouts/PageLayout.astro";
import Container from "@components/Container.astro";
import BackToPrev from "@components/BackToPrev.astro";
import FormattedDate from "@components/FormattedDate.astro";

const title = "Data Lakehouse Research";
const description =
  "A survey of the Data Lakehouse architecture: motivation, design principles, open table formats (Delta Lake, Apache Iceberg, Apache Hudi), and its position between Data Warehouses and Data Lakes.";
const date = new Date("2026-04-25");
const readingTime = "12 min read";

const authors = [
  { name: "Virdio Samuel Saragih", affiliation: "ITERA, Data Science" },
];

const tags = [
  "Data Lakehouse",
  "Delta Lake",
  "Apache Iceberg",
  "Apache Hudi",
  "Big Data",
  "Data Engineering",
];
---

<PageLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Container>
    <div class="animate">
      <BackToPrev href="/papers">Back to papers</BackToPrev>
    </div>

    <header class="space-y-3 my-10">
      <div class="animate flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm opacity-75">
        <FormattedDate date={date} />
        &bull;
        <span>{readingTime}</span>
        &bull;
        <span>Research note</span>
      </div>

      <h1 class="animate text-2xl font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
        {title}
      </h1>

      <p class="animate text-sm opacity-75">
        {
          authors.map((a, i) => (
            <span>
              <span class="text-black dark:text-white">{a.name}</span>
              <span class="opacity-75"> &mdash; {a.affiliation}</span>
              {i < authors.length - 1 ? <span>, </span> : null}
            </span>
          ))
        }
      </p>

      <ul class="animate flex flex-wrap gap-2 pt-2">
        {
          tags.map((tag) => (
            <li class="text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded border border-black/15 dark:border-white/20 opacity-80">
              {tag}
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </header>

    <article class="animate space-y-10 text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          Abstract
        </h2>
        <p>
          The <strong>Data Lakehouse</strong> is an emerging data management
          architecture that combines the low-cost, flexible storage of a
          <em>data lake</em> with the transactional guarantees and performance
          of a <em>data warehouse</em>. This note surveys the motivation
          behind the lakehouse, reviews the enabling open table formats
          (Delta Lake, Apache Iceberg, Apache Hudi), and discusses practical
          trade-offs when adopting a lakehouse in modern data platforms.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          1. Background &amp; Motivation
        </h2>
        <p>
          Traditional analytics stacks evolved in two stages. First, the
          <strong>Data Warehouse</strong> (DWH) offered ACID transactions,
          schema enforcement, and fast SQL analytics, but at a high cost and
          with limited support for unstructured data. Second, the
          <strong>Data Lake</strong> emerged on top of cheap object storage
          (S3, GCS, ADLS), handling raw and semi-structured data at scale,
          but sacrificing transactional correctness and query performance.
        </p>
        <p>
          A typical organization ended up with a <em>two-tier architecture</em>:
          a data lake for raw/ML workloads and a warehouse for BI. This
          duplication introduced staleness, cost overhead, and governance
          complexity. The lakehouse directly targets that pain by bringing
          warehouse-like capabilities onto the lake.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          2. Core Design Principles
        </h2>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
          <li>
            <span class="text-black dark:text-white">Open storage formats:</span>
            data is stored in columnar files (Parquet, ORC) on object storage,
            accessible by any engine.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="text-black dark:text-white">Transactional metadata layer:</span>
            a table format (Delta, Iceberg, Hudi) sits on top of the files and
            provides ACID, schema evolution, and time travel.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="text-black dark:text-white">Separation of storage and compute:</span>
            multiple engines (Spark, Trino, Flink, DuckDB) can read and write
            the same table concurrently.
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="text-black dark:text-white">Unified workloads:</span>
            BI, streaming, data science, and ML all target the same table of
            truth.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          3. Reference Architecture
        </h2>
        <pre class="p-4 rounded border border-black/15 dark:border-white/20 overflow-x-auto text-xs"><code>{`┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              Consumption Layer               │
│   BI  │  Notebooks  │  ML  │  Reverse ETL    │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    ▲
                    │   SQL / DataFrame
                    ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              Compute Engines                 │
│   Spark │  Trino  │  Flink  │  DuckDB        │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    ▲
                    │   Reads/Writes
                    ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│        Open Table Format (ACID Layer)        │
│   Delta Lake   │   Iceberg   │   Hudi        │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    ▲
                    │
                    ▼
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│      Object Storage (Parquet / ORC)          │
│            S3 / GCS / ADLS / MinIO           │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘`}</code></pre>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          4. Open Table Formats
        </h2>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
            4.1 Delta Lake
          </h3>
          <p>
            Originated at Databricks. Uses a transaction log (<code
              >_delta_log</code
            >) with JSON and checkpoint Parquet files to record atomic commits
            over Parquet data. Strong ecosystem around Spark and Databricks,
            with increasing support in Trino, Flink, and DuckDB.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
            4.2 Apache Iceberg
          </h3>
          <p>
            Designed at Netflix for petabyte-scale tables. Uses a hierarchical
            metadata tree (metadata file, manifest list, manifests) to enable
            partition evolution, hidden partitioning, and consistent
            snapshots. Highly engine-agnostic and increasingly a de facto
            standard in multi-engine environments.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-2">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
            4.3 Apache Hudi
          </h3>
          <p>
            Built at Uber around streaming-first ingestion. Offers two table
            types &mdash; Copy-on-Write and Merge-on-Read &mdash; that trade
            write amplification against read latency. Strong upsert and CDC
            story, making it a natural fit for incremental pipelines.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          5. Comparison Matrix
        </h2>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-xs border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-black/15 dark:border-white/20">
                <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
                  Aspect
                </th>
                <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
                  Data Warehouse
                </th>
                <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
                  Data Lake
                </th>
                <th class="py-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
                  Data Lakehouse
                </th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="[&>tr]:border-b [&>tr]:border-black/10 dark:[&>tr]:border-white/10">
              <tr>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Storage format</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Proprietary</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Open files</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Open files + table format</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">ACID</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">No</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Yes</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Schema enforcement</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Strong</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Weak</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Strong + evolution</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">ML / unstructured</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Limited</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Excellent</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Excellent</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Cost</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">High</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Low</td>
                <td class="py-2 pr-4">Low &ndash; Medium</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          6. Open Research Questions
        </h2>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-1">
          <li>
            How should catalogs (Unity, Polaris, Nessie, Gravitino) converge to
            a single cross-format governance model?
          </li>
          <li>
            What is the right cost model for compaction, clustering, and
            Z-ordering on top of object storage?
          </li>
          <li>
            Can streaming and batch truly share the same table without
            sacrificing latency or correctness?
          </li>
          <li>
            How do we benchmark lakehouses fairly across Delta, Iceberg, and
            Hudi, without engine bias?
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          7. Conclusion
        </h2>
        <p>
          The lakehouse is not a silver bullet, but it represents a credible
          path toward <em>one copy of the data</em> for analytics, ML, and
          streaming. For most organizations still running a classic
          lake-plus-warehouse stack, adopting an open table format is the
          cheapest, lowest-risk first step toward a lakehouse.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="space-y-3">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
          References
        </h2>
        <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-1">
          <li>
            Armbrust, M. et al. &mdash; <em
              >Lakehouse: A New Generation of Open Platforms that Unify Data
              Warehousing and Advanced Analytics</em
            >, CIDR, 2021.
          </li>
          <li>
            Databricks. &mdash;
            <a
              class="underline underline-offset-2"
              href="https://delta.io"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener">Delta Lake documentation</a
            >.
          </li>
          <li>
            Apache Software Foundation. &mdash;
            <a
              class="underline underline-offset-2"
              href="https://iceberg.apache.org"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener">Apache Iceberg</a
            >.
          </li>
          <li>
            Apache Software Foundation. &mdash;
            <a
              class="underline underline-offset-2"
              href="https://hudi.apache.org"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener">Apache Hudi</a
            >.
          </li>
          <li>
            Kimball, R. &amp; Ross, M. &mdash; <em
              >The Data Warehouse Toolkit (3rd ed.)</em
            >, Wiley, 2013.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>
    </article>
  </Container>
</PageLayout>
